Alright guys. As many of you know I am developing a Screen Sharing application to replace ~~ScreenShitty~~ ScreenHero. Today I am here to tell you that the project took a step back as we are dropping the use of Electron and web development technologies in favor of C++ and QT.

Here is why:

Electron uses a lot of ram/cpu just on its own. Using Electron is a great idea for applications that don’t inherently use a lot of ram/cpu to process. Such as a text editor, music player, chat application. But for something like a screen sharing application which needs to use a lot of ram/cpu to capture, compress, and send images at 15+ FPS we need a fast, native way to create the application.

Let me know what you think. Also we believe we came up with a name. Codare.

We are doing this because few of our Campsite Gitter chatroooms have active synchronous discussions, and about 1/3rd of conversations consist of someone saying “hello” and not getting a response. Most of the discussions are asynchronous, which Facebook posts and group messages are better suited for.
We’ve removed this Gitter room from our Campsite directory. Still, we will keep it open for archival purposes, and you can keep using it if you’d like.

If you have seen pinterest, they has a multi-column interface to display the pins and those pins arrange nicely even if they are not of the same height. They do it by using javascript to calculate the height of each pin and then positioning them absolutely. Achieving the same with CSS can be done in two ways:

Using Floats: Floats can be used but only if all the pins have same height otherwise there will be gaps left all over.
Using CSS3 Columns: This is what I used here. It is explained in detail below.
Javascript is still the way to go as this technique has some problems like, lesser cross browser support, seemed to produce weird bugs while testing that were fixed with weird solutions (although simple), hard to maintain the ordering of the items . If there is any ordering, like you want to show recent items where the first item is most recent, and the second most recent item is on the right, it doesn't maintains that. Also, the ordering changes on resizing so it's not a better option.

Yeah so far I've took a couple courses in college (too easy) and now CS50x (better) on edX in parallel to FCC. Just worried with FCC a bit since it seems like practice so far, and not really nuts and bolts understanding -- I guess that gets covered in the computer science portion -- i.e. javascript and algorithms?

The early waypoints are good intros to the basic fundamentals of web development and the levels beyond those work on more advanced concepts and their fundamentals at a higher level of knowledge if that makes sense.

I can tell you that the ones who have stayed with it and are towards the end are competent enough to effectively be able work on actual real-world projects and I believe around 15 Campers have gotten jobs since the start of FreeCodeCamp just 274 days ago.

It's a great guided course that follows a good path to make you competent in my opinion. With that said you will need to put the time in and will also probably want to supplement some of the curriculum with additional learning on topics that you would benefit in doing that. My advice is to stick with the learning path FCC lays out for you, then devote a portion of your designated learning time each day/week to supplementing with good books, or outside resources focused on the same topics as FCC covers.
